# Docker Cleanup Commands

## Overview

This README explains basic Docker cleanup commands used to stop containers, remove containers, and delete Docker images from a system.

These commands help clean unused Docker resources and free system storage.

---

# 1. Delete All Docker Images

### Command:

```bash
docker rmi -f $(docker images -q)
```

### Description:

This command removes all Docker images from the local Docker environment.

### Explanation:

* `docker images -q`

  * Displays only the image IDs of all Docker images.

* `docker rmi`

  * Removes Docker images.

* `-f`

  * Forces the removal of images.

### Example:

```bash
$ docker images

REPOSITORY     IMAGE ID
ubuntu         abc123
project1       xyz456


$ docker rmi -f $(docker images -q)
```

All Docker images will be deleted.

---

# 2. Stop All Docker Containers

### Command:

```bash
docker stop $(docker ps -a -q)
```

### Description:

This command stops all running Docker containers.

### Explanation:

* `docker ps -a -q`

  * Lists all container IDs.

* `docker stop`

  * Stops running containers.

### Example:

```bash
$ docker ps -a

CONTAINER ID
123456
789101


$ docker stop $(docker ps -a -q)
```

All running containers will be stopped.

---

# 3. Remove All Docker Containers

### Command:

```bash
docker rm $(docker ps -a -q)
```

### Description:

This command removes all stopped Docker containers from the system.

### Explanation:

* `docker ps -a -q`

  * Gets all container IDs.

* `docker rm`

  * Deletes containers.

### Example:

```bash
$ docker rm $(docker ps -a -q)
```

All containers will be removed.

---

# Complete Docker Cleanup Process

Run these commands in order:

### Step 1: Stop all containers

```bash
docker stop $(docker ps -a -q)
```

### Step 2: Remove all containers

```bash
docker rm $(docker ps -a -q)
```

### Step 3: Remove all images

```bash
docker rmi -f $(docker images -q)
```

---

# Warning

These commands will permanently delete:

* All Docker containers
* All Docker images
* Docker application environments

Use these commands carefully, especially on production systems.

